        <span class="stamp">GTC 2026</span>
        <h1>NemoClaw</h1>
        <p class="lede">NVIDIA's enterprise wrapper for OpenClaw — sandboxed, guarded, managed. This is the signal that NVIDIA isn't just supporting the claw ecosystem, they're building the production path.</p>

        <div class="highlight-box">
          <strong>The headline:</strong> Jensen Huang called OpenClaw "the next ChatGPT" at GTC 2026. NemoClaw launched March 16 as an alpha preview — a sandboxed OpenClaw environment with policy-based security guardrails.
        </div>

        <h2>What it does</h2>
        <p>NemoClaw runs OpenClaw inside NVIDIA OpenShell with multiple layers of isolation:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sandboxing:</strong> Landlock + seccomp + network namespaces</li>
          <li><strong>Policy guardrails:</strong> Every network request, file access, and inference call is governed by declarative policy</li>
          <li><strong>Managed inference:</strong> Routes through OpenShell gateway — supports NVIDIA Endpoints, OpenAI, Anthropic, and other OpenAI-compatible providers</li>
          <li>Single-command deploy: <code>curl -fsSL https://www.nvidia.com/nemoclaw.sh | bash</code></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who it's for</h2>
        <p>If you want to run OpenClaw in an enterprise context — with corporate security policies, audit trails, and managed inference — NemoClaw is the path. It's not replacing the open ecosystem, it's wrapping it for production use cases.</p>

